### ðŸ”¹ What is a Queue?

A **queue** is a **linear data structure** that follows the **FIFO (First In, First Out)** principle.
This means the element that is inserted first will be removed first.

**Real-life example:**

* People standing in a line
* Printer job scheduling
* CPU task scheduling

---

### ðŸ”¹ Why Do We Use a Queue?

Queues are used when:

* Order matters (first request served first)
* Tasks must be processed sequentially
* We need fair resource sharing

Common uses:

* Operating systems (process scheduling)
* Networking (packet handling)
* Data buffering
* Breadth First Search (BFS) in graphs

---

### ðŸ”¹ Queue Behavior

A queue has two main operations:

* **Enqueue (push):** Insert element at the **rear**
* **Dequeue (pop):** Remove element from the **front**

Additional operations:

* `front()` â†’ get front element
* `back()` â†’ get last element
* `empty()` â†’ check if queue is empty
* `size()` â†’ number of elements

ðŸ“Œ **FIFO order:**
Insert: 10 â†’ 20 â†’ 30 â†’ 40
Remove: 10 â†’ 20 â†’ 30 â†’ 40

#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
class Node{
    public:
    int val;
    Node* next;
    Node(int val){
        this->val = val;
        this->next=NULL;
    }
};
class LL_Queue{
    public:
    Node* head =NULL;
    Node* tail =NULL;
    int sz = 0;

    void push(int val){
        sz++;
        Node* newnode = new Node(val);
        if(head==NULL){
            head= newnode;
            tail = newnode;
            return;
        }
        tail->next = newnode;
        tail = newnode;
    }
    int front(){
        if(head == NULL)return -1;

        return head->val;
    }
    void pop(){
        if(head == NULL)return;
        sz--;
        head = head->next;
    }
    int size(){
        return sz;
    }
    bool empty(){
        return sz == 0;
    }
    int back(){
        if(head == NULL)return -1;
        return tail->val;
    }
};
int main() {
    LL_Queue llq;
    llq.push(10);
    llq.push(20);
    llq.push(30);
    llq.push(40);
    while(!llq.empty()){
        cout<<llq.front()<<" ";
        llq.pop();
    }
    
    
    return 0;
}

## ðŸ”¹ Code Summary

* This program implements a **queue using a singly linked list**.
* `Node` stores a value and a pointer to the next node.
* `LL_Queue` maintains:

  * `head` â†’ front of the queue
  * `tail` â†’ rear of the queue
  * `sz` â†’ number of elements
* `push()` adds elements at the **rear**.
* `pop()` removes elements from the **front**.
* `front()` and `back()` return front and rear values.
* `size()` and `empty()` help manage queue state.
* In `main()`, values `10, 20, 30, 40` are inserted and printed in **FIFO order**.
